AWS Architecture Series: ECS vs EKS — Choosing the Right Container Platform
Introduction
Containerization has become a core part of modern cloud-native architectures. Running applications in containers improves portability, scalability, and deployment consistency.

In AWS, container workloads are managed using two primary services:

Amazon ECS (Elastic Container Service)
Amazon EKS (Elastic Kubernetes Service)
Both services allow teams to run containerized applications, but they differ in terms of architecture, complexity, and use cases.

For DevOps engineers, choosing between ECS and EKS is an important architectural decision.

In this article, we compare:

